## Nmap Commands

### Basic Port Scan
```bash
nmap 127.0.0.1
nmap 192.168.1.x
```
Shows which ports are open and what services are running.

### Version Detection
```bash
nmap -sV 192.168.1.x
```
Shows what software version is running behind each open port.

### OS Detection
```bash
sudo nmap -O 192.168.1.x
```
Tries to detect what operating system the device is running.

### Aggressive Scan (All In One)
```bash
sudo nmap -A 192.168.1.x
```
Runs port scan + version detection + OS detection + script scanning all at once.

### Skip Ping Check (Find Hidden Devices)
```bash
nmap -Pn 192.168.1.x
```
Windows machines hide from normal ping scans. Use -Pn to scan them anyway.

### Scan Entire Network
```bash
nmap 192.168.1.0/24
```
Scans all 254 devices on your local network.

### Faster Network Scan
```bash
nmap -Pn --open -T4 192.168.1.0/24
```

| Flag | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `-Pn` | Skip ping — scan hidden devices |
| `--open` | Show only devices with open ports |
| `-T4` | Scan faster (T1=slowest, T5=fastest) |

